00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:01.209
So what happened to alchemy?

00:11:01.209 --> 00:11:03.970
Parts of it became chemistry, which we’ll
get to later.

00:11:03.970 --> 00:11:09.430
But alchemy also became increasingly seen
as dirty, dangerous, unsavory, low-class,

00:11:09.430 --> 00:11:12.680
and lacking a classical pedigree, unlike,
say, astronomy.

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:17.829
And, in Europe, alchemy was tied to a geocentric
cosmology that goes out of fashion in the

00:11:17.829 --> 00:11:19.269
sixteenth century.

00:11:19.269 --> 00:11:23.339
There were notable alchemists in the seventeenth
century, including Isaac Newton.

00:11:23.339 --> 00:11:27.230
But by this time, chemists wanted a more scientific
society.

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:32.499
Publicly, alchemy was attacked as superstition,
even as practitioners keep doing it in private.

00:11:32.499 --> 00:11:37.070
Alchemy went underground for most of the eighteenth
century, maintained in secret societies, before

00:11:37.070 --> 00:11:38.170
dying out.

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:43.910
The once-famous book De re metallica, or Concerning
the Nature of Metals, was first translated

00:11:43.910 --> 00:11:45.951
into English by classicist Herbert Hoover—

00:11:45.951 --> 00:11:51.600
who was also a president—and his wife, Lou
Henry Hoover, in 1912.

00:11:51.600 --> 00:11:52.720
Fascinating!

